segments.text: That data was coming in and I thought it was being analyzed and we haven't... Oh, you don't have it for the earlier ones either.
So I don't have a good perspective.
I've glanced at it, but in a raw form.
Roughly though, about 40% of our people are going in and teaching.
But that's of those who plan to go in and teach.
Now of those who... Of all of our graduates, about 40% of them will be teacher preparation graduates.
Of those...
it's looking like maybe 60% of them are going into teaching.
Well, that's kind of bad.
It's not bad, and I'm not sure of that number.

Well, I wonder because, you know, like I said, I'm hearing so many different versions of, you know, the numbers and because of teacher shortages, and now what is this going to do to us, this new, if the whole teacher preparation, how is that going to affect your department if this goes into effect, this five-year program and all that other good stuff?
Yeah, that's...
That has really got us in a dither right now.
Dean Corrigan obviously wants it to happen, and every way we turn it, it looks like it's bad for us.
Really?
It's bad for several departments, is it not?
I mean, some of them more so than others.
I mean, that's what I'm hearing from others.
I'm sure everyone thinks that.
Well, who is it good for then?
And why are we doing it?
It's good if this could come about, if.

If we, in fact, did begin to prepare lead teachers, teachers who are obviously better prepared than other schools who are not doing it, and if, and both of these pieces are absolutely essential, and if the public schools recognize that and pay this according, then it would be good.
Because we need research schools who are preparing one level of teaching, and other types of schools are preparing another level.
Dean Corrigan's position is that you've got to decide who comes first, the chicken or the egg, and no one knows.
So what he's decided to do is push to prepare the egg, and then we'll see if the chicken follows.
That's probably an oversimplification of his position.
It's scary, I think it is.
We've gone to a nine-semester curriculum two years ago,
That's one semester past normal graduation.
So it wouldn't be that hard for us to go another semester to have a five-year program.
But it depends on how you let us look when we do that.
What we're talking about now is graphically different than what we've got in place now.
I think we'll turn out a poorer product in our field.
I think the product will be poorer.
I know that our master's people will be poorer.
I thought it would not affect us.
Oh, the master's, okay.
Because right now you have a totally separate or different type of master's program.
Our master's program will be this particular master's, the master of education, will be EDCI, basically.
That makes EDCI program stronger, but it doesn't do anything for a health educator.
A health educator would be stronger in pedagogy, but not stronger in health education.
Now,
I don't object to that because a lot of our people do that anyway.
A lot of our health education majors and physical education majors get a baccalaureate degree with us and then get their masters in EDCM or Ed Psych or someplace else.
But they make that choice.
Under this system, everybody would do that.
And I'm not sure that's good.
Do you still require or do you require of your student teachers the same as the college does, a whole semester?
Yes, that's correct.
That's pretty much.
That's correct.
Okay.
Any type of insights or anecdotes or observations and things that might be, that would not be in any documents, that are just from your own vantage point of where you've sat these last few years?
I had trouble with that when I read it the first time through.
Well, I think... One thing that happened that's in light of what we were just talking about is when I came here in 1972,
We were knee-deep in something called performance-based teacher education.
Remember that?
PBTE.
Texas Education Agency had just decreed that every school, every college preparation program would have to go to a PBTE type of program.
Now, being a junior faculty member, I didn't get involved in a lot of the committee work.
And being a first-year junior faculty member, especially.
But I watched my colleagues just work themselves silly trying to get all that done.
And then about the time they were almost ready to put in place, suddenly it was gone.
And that is something that I worry about in terms of 9-94.
All these personnel that are going into this planning, and the whole thing could change in the next legislature just overnight.
That's by way of an antidote, I guess, but I'm not sure.
What was the base, because I wasn't really in education that much at the time, the performance base, what was the
the major thrust of that movement?
Well, the idea was that you were going to give paramount attention to the performance.
What are your performance objectives?
Okay, yeah.
And everybody was going to have to describe in performance objectives what attention... Not necessarily wrong, wasn't it?
It wasn't necessarily a bad idea.
But unfortunately, a lot of the things that are valuable...
this is my opinion, but a lot of people who, a lot of things that are valuable cannot be reduced to a performance-based objective.
And a lot of it was performance rather than knowledge-based.
It was, you're talking about, can you do this, can you do that, and can you perform that?
It's a good idea, and it moved us forward, I think, in our thinking, in teacher education and in education in general.
But when you
When you try to make the whole world at one way, it's a good case of trying to make the whole world at one way.
Could you give me a very brief profile of your students as they come in?
And do you have a lot of them that start in as freshmen?
Because overall in the college, the freshman class is considerably smaller than what that same class graduates
Is that true in your department?
Do you have a lot of transfer ends?
We mimic the college almost verbatim, maybe even more so.
We will have very few intern freshmen.
We're trying to turn that around.
We've got about a half million dollars' worth of scholarships available, and we would like to use those scholarship dollars to attract incoming freshmen.
But I don't think we want to be successful, frankly.
This school, you know, unless it changes drastically, is an engineering, business, agriculture school.
And 90% of the students who come here, initially come here, to major in one of those fields.
And it's because of their parents, or who knows why, but they all come for those reasons.
And then after they've been here a while, and demonstrated to their parents that this is not for me,
or demonstrate to themselves this is not for me.
Then they began to look around at where they really wanted to be all along.
And I think that's probably true in my field anyway.
Health education and physical education have never been the prestige academic programs of choice anyway, though we were in them.
I think so, but I didn't start it.
I was going to be a pharmacist.
I was going to be a pharmacist because I heard they made a lot of money and it was a good job.
But that wasn't at all what I wanted to do.
And so I went for a semester or two in a pre-pharmacy type program until I finally decided happiness was equally as important as money.
And I think that happens in our field more than even in education, but it's happening in education as well.
More and more and more.
And has the quality of the student changed in your department as much as it has in the overall college?
I don't know in the overall college, but our quality has gone up every year since I've been here.
We get an excellent student, just an excellent student.
One of the things that's happened, and not since I've been here, but it's happened to our field, is that we're no longer the major choice for the athlete.
And I'm not sure.
down on athletics.
I have an athletic background of my own.
I believe very strongly in that.
In athletics, I think it's important, but that's not their choice for us.
We're not their choice anymore.
We have a number of them, but the curriculum has become more rigorous over the years.
It's become more academic, less coaching related, and our student enrollment has, the quality has gone up consistently.
In fact, if you look at our health education people, they will compete with anybody on this campus.
Anybody on this campus.
A lot of the folks in health education are in pre-physical therapy, for example.
And I don't know how familiar you are with physical therapy, but that curriculum is very difficult to get into.
They interview about 30 people for every one person they take.
They tell me that it's even more difficult to get into physical therapy now than it is to get into medicine.
medicine has gotten to where it's about a three-to-one relationship.
Is that part of the College of Medicine?
Our health education program serves a number of those people to get necessary prerequisites.
And then there's five programs in the state.
San Antonio has one, UT at San Antonio.
Galveston has one.
TWU in Houston has one, Texas Tech has one, and UT at Dallas has one.
So it's five programs.
And a lot of our folks are going through a pre-nursing curriculum as well.
So we get a broad-based type of student in health education.
Exercise Tech folks have been very, very high quality.
In fact, we've had two students who've used that program as a pre-med curriculum.
One of them got her degree in medicine this past time, and another one is in her second year in med school.
Well, is there anything that you would like to close this with?
Anything in particular?
I don't know, again, what focus this, how I want to use all this dissertation.
Like I said, I have not talked to anybody in your department, and maybe there's somebody that I need to talk to other than you've been here quite a while, and I know...
Several people mentioned Dr. Landis, and if I can't, I know he's retired now, Ron.
That's right, but he's in town a lot.
But I might be able to visit with him.
Dr. Landis would be a good person.
There's two faculty members that would have been here longer than I.
Three, in fact.
Okay.
One is Linus Dow, D-O-W-E-L-L, and Jack Chivret.
Okay.
I had gone through the videos to pick out ones that had been, and I had a couple of them.
I just, the time element, I might try to do some by telephone from San Antonio and just have a tape recorder thing that catches on because I, physically, I'm having, now that I have a full-time job.
Oh, yeah, you've got lots to do.
But I really appreciate your time and the interview and your perceptions, and I hope that you'll let me come back if I have a question or if I call you.
